<TITLE> UK permanent jobs growth slows to 13-month low-KPMG </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Nov 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Permanent job placements rose at their slowest pace in more than a year in October but ongoing skill shortages pushed wages slightly higher, a survey showed on Wednesday. The KPMG/Recruitment and Employment Federation Report on Jobs showed the index for permanent placements fell from 60.2 to 57.4, its lowest since September 2006. The temporary placements index rose to a three-month high, suggesting economic uncertainty is encouraging firms to make short-term rather than long-term commitments. "The credit crunch begins to cast a shadow over the job market," said Alan Nolan, Director at KPMG. "If this trend continues we may see job losses across the sectors which are particularly volatile." Vacancies for permanent positions rose at their slowest pace in 17 months. However, evidence the labour market is softening had little impact on wages which picked up last month from a 13-month low. The index of salaries for permanent staff rose to 61.9 from 61.1 in September, while that for temporary staff ticked up to 59.5 from 59
